<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Mark Nohl -- Special to the Mercury News; European-style Taos
Ski Valley is just 20 miles from Taos  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  SKIING; NEW-MEXICO  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  HERE in "The Land of Enchantment" you can ski on an Apache reservation, on a
ski area designed by Los Alamos rocket scientists, or on a 12,000-foot peak
just 16 miles from the margaritas and blue corn tortillas at the Coyote Cafe
in downtown Santa Fe.;   And that doesn't even include Taos, the state's
best-known ski resort and the one that most resembles a Swiss alpine village,
or Red River, the funky little ski area up the road from Taos that's a
favorite of Texans.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Travel  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  FOR DOWNHILL ENCHANTMENT, TEST NEW MEXICO'S SLOPES,
TASTE SANTA FE'S CHARMS;  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Skiing: A Special Section; See also related article on page 1T &amp; 4T-9T of this
section.; Free-lance writer Glen Putman lives in Los Altos.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Compared to Colorado, Utah or the High Sierra, New Mexico skiing is still
relatively unknown. But that's changing. Given the historic architecture,
multicultural traditions, savory cuisine, beautiful art -- and some truly
big-league skiing -- the state is rapidly gaining popularity with skiers
around the country. In fact, last ski season, New Mexico posted a new high in
total skier days (1,157,604), and three individual areas (Taos, Santa Fe Ski
Area and Angel Fire) logged their best years ever. And this was accomplished
with only eight alpine ski areas and one cross-country area. The lack of snow
elsewhere last year helped bring many first-time visitors to New Mexico ski
areas. I was one of those and I was not disappointed.;   One of the best
things about skiing in New Mexico is that you almost certainly will spend some
time in Santa Fe. If you did nothing but discover this charming city of
museums, art galleries and nationally acclaimed restaurants, you would be
fulfilled. Volumes thicker than the substantial adobe walls of the local
buildings have been written about the charms of Santa Fe. 'Tis true, 'tis
true. But on to the ski slopes:;   Taos;   For the skier, most of what little
attention New Mexico has received has been given to Taos Ski Valley, the
legendary area developed in the European style by the late Ernie Blake, a
Swiss wunderkind who used to hide tiny bottles of martinis in the trees around
Al's Rug, the showcase expert trail that dumps out at the base lodge. Given
some of the steep chutes at Taos, consumption of liquid courage might be
understandable. At this area, believe it when you see a double black diamond
run. Blake, a ski pioneer revered in the industry, developed the ski area as
his vision of the perfect ski resort. Many think he came pretty close.;   The
ski area provides breathtaking steeps and deep bowls of fluffy powder. The
immense peaks and steep terrain are what first lured Blake to the area in the
early 1950s. Some 51 percent of the terrain is rated "expert." The peak
stretches to 11,819 feet, with a vertical drop of 2,612 feet. However, Blake
also carved out open bowls and wide gentle trails (25 percent intermediate, 24
percent beginner). Eight chairlifts serve some 72 runs.;   Taos Ski Valley
(base elevation 9,207 feet) is nestled in the Sangre de Cristo ("Blood of
Christ") mountains, 20 miles from the historic Spanish town of Taos. In Taos
you can visit hundreds of shops, galleries and fine restaurants. At the
800-year-old Taos Pueblo, Native American residents live in a style close to
the pastoral existence of a bygone day.;   With an average annual snowfall of
306 inches, a lack of snow is not usually a problem. However, this year Taos
Ski Valley will increase snowmaking by 30 percent, with man-made snow possible
on 85 percent of the beginner and intermediate trails. A quad chair will
replace the Kachina lift and substantially increase uphill capacity in the
popular Kachina Bowl. An adult lift ticket is $34, multi-day, $31. The area
plans to open Nov. 28 and operate through April 5. For lodging reservations,
call (800) 992-7669.;   Ski Apache;   The ski patrolmen don't wear eagle
feathers in their caps, but with trails aptly named Geronimo, Ambush and
Apache Bowl, you get the idea. Ski Apache is not really a different kind of
ski resort, except it boasts the only gondola in the state. Located in south
central New Mexico, smack in the middle of a Mescalero Apache Reservation
bordering the Lincoln National Forest, Ski Apache might be the state's most
pleasant surprise for skiers.;   The area features the largest lift capacity
in the state and is a pleasing variety of bowl and trail skiing that offers
enough black diamond excitement for the experts and some nice blue cruisers
for intermediates. General manager Roy Parker, a 29-year ski-industry veteran,
held key jobs at Vail and Aspen before being lured by the Mescaleros in 1964
to run the area that was then known as Sierra Blanca, named for the
magnificent 12,003-foot peak that dominates the view for miles around.;   The
ski area sits on the northwest flank of the peak and the reservation boundary
parallels the Elk Ridge run and the Apache Bowl triple chair lift. Outstanding
expert runs such as Wild Onion (so good it brought tears to my eyes)and
Screaming Eagle are not actually on tribal lands. Both are reached by riding
the gondola to the 11,400-foot Gazebo. You can ski in and out of the
reservation in seconds and you'll never know the difference.;   Ruidoso, 200
miles southeast of Albuquerque and 130 miles north of El Paso, is the gateway
to Ski Apache. The ski area is just 16 miles away on a road that offers a
breathtaking ride and a chance to spot an eagle along the way. Ruidoso means
"noisy water," and is dubbed the "Year-Around Playground of the Southwest." A
food tip: When in Ruidoso, don't miss the Mountain Bayou restaurant, owned and
operated by Angela McVickers and her husband, Allen. Angela is a West Texas
beauty who trained in New Orleans, and her crawfish, chicken gumbo and
blackened salmon could dance down Bourbon Street. Allen's babyback ribs take a
backseat to none.;   The base elevation of Ski Apache is 9,600 feet
(11,500-foot summit) and the average snowfall is 185 inches a year. Advance
runs account for 45 percent of the trails, with 30 percent intermediate. The
vertical drop is 1,900 feet. Snowmaking covers 45 acres on the lower one-third
of the mountain. There are seven chairs plus the gondola. A new 3,000-foot
quad chair will operate this season along Elk Ridge, which will open up
another 150 acres of skiing. Daily lift tickets are $31 for adults ($28
multi-day) and $19 for children.;   The Inn of the Mountain Gods is a
Four-Diamond Mobil resort nestled in the Sacramento Mountains at 7,200 feet.
The scenic and serene resort is in the heart of the 460,000 forested acres of
the Mescalero reservation and is owned and operated by tribe members. Most of
the 240 rooms and suites overlook beautiful Lake Mescalero and from every
angle, the stunning, snowcapped Sierra Blanca commands the view.;   According
to Mescalero stories, the mountain was the birthplace of two sons of the
"White Painted Woman." Legend says the two grew to be brave warriors who
killed off monsters threatening the survival of the tribe. The reservation was
established in 1873 and the resort was the dream of Tribal Chief Wendell
Chino, who chose the site so that it viewed the sacred tribal grounds. The
resort opened in 1975. The resort was to provide a training ground and job
center for members of the three Mescalero Apache subtribes -- Mescalero, Lipan
and Chiricahua.;   The resort is a delight. You can do nothing, or do a lot.
One day in early March, I skied about 10 great runs, grabbed a quick lunch and
scampered down the mountain to play nine holes of golf and a set of tennis
before cocktail hour.;   A double room November through mid-April at the Inn
of the Mountain Gods runs $80; $95 during the holidays. For more information
on ski packages and lodging, call the Inn at (800) 545-9011 or the ski area,
(505) 336-4356.;   Santa Fe Ski Area;   If I could only ski one area in New
Mexico, this would be it. And for two very simple reasons: The proximity to
the quintessential Southwestern town of the same name, and, some surprisingly
tasty runs (Parachute and Thunderbird in particular) on a mountain that boasts
a base elevation of 10,350 feet and a 12,000-foot summit. With a vertical drop
of 1,650 feet, an average annual snowfall of 250 inches and close enough to
Santa Fe to smell the green chili simmering at Josie's, this is my kind of
place.;   Forty percent of the 38 runs at Santa Fe are rated expert and the
same percentage are intermediate. An adult lift ticket is $30, $27 for
multi-day. A child's ticket is $18 or $15, multi-day. Lodging packages are
available with a four-night, three-day ski package as low as $160 per person.
For reservations and information, call (800) 982-7669. For the ski area, call
(505) 982-4429.  </TEXT>
