<DESCRIPT>  JUDGE; ATTEMPT; CHANGE; COURT; CRIME; SENTENCE; AMERICAN-; INDIAN  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  When Patrick "Hooty" Croy arrived Wednesday at the ornate old courthouse here
in the foothills of the Gold Country, he and his supporters held little hope
he could win a reprieve from a life sentence in prison for smoking marijuana.;
   But at the end of an extraordinary hourlong proceeding, during which Croy's
attorney told Placer County Judge Richard Gilbert that the sentence was so
harsh it could undermine any faith Indians might have in the courts, it was
the judge who asked for mercy.;    "Don't come in here and tell me I'm some
racist arbitrary person," Gilbert said. " . . . Show me the leniency you would
have me give Croy," the judge said, his voice dropping almost to a whisper.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  JUDGE HINTS HE'LL RESCIND LIFE TERM FOR EX-CONVICT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  SETTING THE RECORD STRAIGHT (publ. 4/5/91, pg. 2A);  Because of an editor's
error, some editions of Thursday's Mercury News included a headline
incorrectly summarizing court action against Patrick "Hooty" Croy. Placer
County Judge Richard Gilbert scheduled a hearing to reconsider his order
sending Croy back to prison for life after Croy violated his probation by
smoking marijuana.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "There should be mutual forgiveness," replied Croy's attorney, Tony Serra.
"Give us another hearing.";    It was granted, and Croy, a Shasta-Karuk Indian
whose acquittal on murder charges and release from death row last year became
a symbol of justice for Indians, left the courtroom beaming, his clenched fist
raised in salute to friends and relatives.;    Judge sets April 30 hearing; 
Gilbert made no promises but indicated he would rescind his earlier order
sending Croy to back to prison for life if Croy could find a private halfway
house where he could serve his probation with some supervision. Gilbert set a
hearing on the issue for April 30.;    Placer County Assistant District
Attorney Thomas Beattie, who a day earlier had bragged confidently to a
reporter that Croy had almost no chance of changing the judge's mind, drew
loud gasps in the courtroom with an objection that giving Croy another chance
"would be like giving a dog a second chance to bite.";    Beattie's words
seemed to linger in the air, echoing in the same Auburn courthouse where an
all-white jury in 1979 had judged Croy guilty of murder.;    Serra later
called Beattie's comments "the embodiment of all the racist bias we've been
fighting for five years.";    Acquitted in cop's killing;  Croy was accused of
murder in the shooting death of Yreka police officer Jesse "Bo" Hittson during
a 1978 gunbattle at a desolate moonlit hillside in Siskiyou County. After the
1979 trial, which was moved to Placer County because of extensive publicity,
the California Supreme Court overturned Croy's conviction in 1985.;    At a
retrial last May, a San Francisco jury acquitted Croy of murder. He won his
freedom -- only the second death row inmate to do so under California's
current capital punishment law -- after presenting a "cultural defense" based
on the state's long history of racism against Indians.;    Serra successfully
argued that Croy, shot twice in the back, believed that sheriff's deputies
still harbored a frontier mentality toward Indians and wanted to kill him.
Croy shot Hittson once through the heart in self-defense, Serra said.;    
Life term suspended;  But the high court had not thrown out Croy's conviction
on conspiracy to commit murder. After the acquittal on the murder charge,
Judge Gilbert sentenced Croy to life in prison on the remaining charge. He
suspended execution of the sentence, however, and placed him on probation for
10 years. By the time Croy was released at age 33, he had served 12 years in
prison.;    When drug tests in December and again in January showed that Croy
had smoked marijuana, Gilbert ordered him back to prison to serve his life
sentence.;    On Wednesday, Serra rebuked the judge for the harshness of the
sentence and called it unprecedented.;    The order "sends out a message to
the community throughout this country that the courts are openly not fair to
Indian people," Serra charged.;     Judge visibly shocked;  Gilbert, visibly
stung by the accusation, said he had prayed Croy would be able to succeed on
his own but feared he would not.;    After the hearing Wednesday, Serra and
other supporters acknowledged that the celebrity status and massive popular
support that helped Croy gain his freedom may also have made it harder to
adjust later when, as the judge put it, the "glitter goes away.";    Bobby
Castillo, a friend of Croy's and a Chiricahua Apache Indian, said he, too, had
served many years in prison and knew how difficult it was to adjust to life
outside.;    "The first two years out were even harder than being in prison,"
Castillo said. "I was with Hooty after the first time he smoked marijuana and
he was feeling really bad. He was very lonely. You know you can be free and
still feel lonely.;    "This court wants Hooty to be assimilated into white
society. But we need to take Hooty back and be an Indian again. We need to
take him on the red road."  </TEXT>
<BYLINE>  MIRANDA EWELL, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE>
