<HEAD>Rights Commission Head Apologizes to Apache Leader in Custody Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the U.S. Civil Rights
Commission apologized for his conduct on an Apache reservation in
Arizona, but argued that his intentions in interviewing a
14-year-old girl there were practically heroic.
   Chairman William B. Allen, in letters released Monday by the
commission, compared himself to Lenny Skutnick, who in January 1982
dived into the icy Potomac River to save victims of an Air Florida
airliner crash in the capital.
   Allen, on orders from other commission members, wrote to Lalita
Altaha and her parents. ``I'm just an ordinary Skutnick, who dove
into the cold water when the time came,'' he said in both letters.
``I am happy I was able to do that much.''
   But the commission chairman also said he regretted the events of
Feb. 7 and apologized in another letter to the chairman of the
White Mountain Apache Nation.
   Allen and commission consultant Barry Goodfield, accompanied by
an NBC television crew, had taken the child into their car and
interviewed her after picking her up at a reservation school.
   The girl complained in the interview that she was ``an outcast''
on the reservation. She had been reared by a white family that
adopted her and took her off the reservation as a baby. A tribal
court nullified the adoption, and the girl recently was returned to
her natural parents.
   Her natural mother, Thurza Altaha, angrily brushed off Allen's
questions when he and Goodfield arrived at their home with the
girl. Mrs. Altaha called tribal police to complain that the men had
abducted the girl from her school bus.
   Tribal police got Gila County sheriff's deputies to arrest Allen
and Goodfield as they were returning to Phoenix. Deputies
confronted the civil rights official with drawn guns. Both men were
released without charges after being held for several hours.
   Allen said he went to Arizona to look into child custody matters
involving Indians. Goodfield, a psychologist who works with the
commission, also had been advising Normand and Nadine Desrocher in
their efforts to retain custody of Mrs. Altaha's daughter.
   Last week, the other seven members of the civil rights panel
demanded that Allen apologize for his actions on the reservation.
   Some commissioners also had called for his resignation, saying
he had embarrassed President Bush. Allen, in turn, suggested the
commission was an embarrassment to the president and suggested they
all resign. Four of the eight commission members are appointed by
the president and the other four by Congress; all serve staggered
six-year terms.
   Allen last week said he would not resign unless Bush personally
asked him to do so. White House spokesman Stephen Hart said Bush
had no intention of asking Allen to step down and would not have a
vacancy to fill on the commission until November.
   Bush can appoint a new chairman from among commission members
anytime he can get a majority of the commission to approve the
appointment.
   Allen, in his letter to tribal Chairman Reno Johnson, said he
had already expressed ``deep regret'' for events of Feb. 7 after
his ``false arrest.''
   ``I apologize to you again. And I would repeat it tomorrow and
the day after,'' Allen wrote, adding, ``I would insist, however,
that wherever I err I do so in the honest fulfillment of my
obligations to my country.''
   In an apology to the girl's parents, he said: ``I came as a
member of the Commission on Civil Rights, seeking information in a
matter which in my judgment is of grave importance to the safety of
the rights which you enjoy under the Constitution.
   ``I regret that my attempt to understand came at the cost of so
much publicity and confusion to you and your family.''
   On Friday, tribal attorney Claudeen Bates Arthur accused Allen
of having ``a racially discriminatory attitude about Indian
children'' and called for his resignation.
   She said Allen seemed to think it was all right ``to do this to
an Indian child on an Indian reservation, whereas you wouldn't find
such conduct acceptable in middle-class white society.''
</TEXT>
