<HEAD>Indian Firefighters Sought By Agencies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROSE ANA BERBEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There is a small village north of
Albuquerque where people wait all summer to hear a siren's wail.
   It is a call to action for the Indians of Pueblo Jemez, renowned
for their ability to fight wildfires. Somewhere, there is a fire,
and the first ones to reach the town's community center will be
hired to fight it.
   ``Everybody, whether they're naked or eating or whatever, has to
run. That's when the physical training comes in handy,'' said
Lawrence Tosa, who coordinates the Jemez crews.
   Similar crews from Navajo, Hopi, Apache, Zuni and smaller tribes
are called upon each year as fires flare across the country.
Wildfires that closed Yosemite Park for the first time in its
history were battled by crews that included Apaches from eastern
Arizona.
   Other recent California fires have been fought by Northern
Cheyenne, Acoma, Santo Domingo, Taos, Mescalero and Navajo crews,
said Dennis Orrick, fire intelligence officer for the state
Department of Forestry and Fire Protection.
   The Indians do everything from digging fire lines to lugging
water pumps.
   ``They're invaluable to us. If they were not available, we'd
have real difficulty finding other people to fill that void,'' said
Lee Singer, public affairs officer for the Cibola National Forest.
   ``They're really known for their ability to work, their
endurance,'' said Ray Kirgan, a fire management officer for the
Bureau of Indian Affairs.
   ``They come from the mountain region. They are hunters, they do
woodcutting, they've fought bears in the woods. They know how to do
the work without being told. It's almost automatic,'' he said.
   Kirgan, 51, should know. An Apache firefighter for 30 years, he
still can pass the strenuous step test, a physical fitness
requirement.
   Indians always have been firefighters on their own land, but it
wasn't until after World War II that they turned to firefighting
for the U.S. government as a source of income.
   ``People were back from the war and employment was down,'' said
Kirgan. ``They were living off the land and they were trying to get
some income. So they started organizing.''
   The Mescaleros Apaches of southern New Mexico were the first
Indian firefighters to be exported when they were sent to help
battle a California fire in 1948, Kirgan said. The Bureau of Indian
Affairs trained them, gave them hard hats and sent them to work
alongside the Forest Service crews.
   They were so good that ``other states just started calling,''
Kirgan said. In New Mexico each spring, 150 to 200 Mescalero
Apaches apply for firefighting jobs. About 50 are hired and go
through three days of training; they then are on call 24 hours a
day. If called to a fire, they may work 12- to 16-hour shifts for
14 days without a break. Base pay is $7.98 an hour.
   It's seasonal, undependable and dangerous work, but for Indians
like Clemente Toledo, summer firefighting is an important source of
income.
   ``You make more money in fewer hours, at a faster pace,'' said
Toledo, 32, who grows corn and chili on his farm and works at odd
construction jobs. Like most Indian reservations and pueblos, Jemez
suffers high unemployment.
   Toledo, slim and muscular, is a crew boss responsible for
coordinating about 15 men at a fire. In five years, he has been
sent to fires in Northern California, Tennessee, West Virginia and
elsewhere.
   He spent 29 days in Oregon in 1988: ``There was a lot of work, a
lot of hours, and the food was great. We were there for 29 days. On
my two days of R&amp;R, I toured the coastline, ate pizza and got
T-shirts made for the crew.''
   The Jemez crews, known as the Eagles, achieved national fame in
the 1950s and 1960s when they were recognized as the top
firefighters in the country.
   There has been one major change since that time: In Jemez and
elsewhere, women began joining the firefighting ranks in the late
1970s.
   Reyes Panana, 29, a mother of three who has been separated from
her husband for more than a year, joined the Jemez roster this fire
season after waiting for several years. She's one of 15 women
firefighters.
   The issue of women's rights didn't influence her decision to try
her hand at firefighting, she said. She just needed a job.
   And the men don't treat the women firefighters any differently,
she said.
   ``We enjoy ourselves when we get back to camp. We talk to each
other. We share. We work together,'' she said.
   When her grandfather died in 1982, Panana, a ninth-grade
dropout, looked for a way to feed and clothe her children. She took
up pottery, which she sells to tourists. But pottery doesn't bring
in much money; firefighting does.
   ``At first, my kids were scared for me to go to a fire. . . .
They started crying that first fire,'' she said.
   They had heard about the deaths of four Jemez firefighters in a
1986 car accident at an Idaho forest fire, and ``They thought I
wasn't going to come back,'' she said.
   ``Now they're excited because of the money I've been bringing
home and the things I've been buying them. I bought them bunkbeds,
clothes and shoes.''
   Tosa said his firefighters don't get hazard pay or benefits, and
he wishes they did. But, he's quick to add, ``If they went out
there for the money, they would sit around all day doing nothing
and get the same money.
   ``They are professionals. They have pride in what they're doing.
It's a family sort of attitude. They all put in the same effort,''
he said.
   ``The only reward I really hope for and pray for is to bring all
my people home standing on their own two feet. And the faces I see
on payday.''
</TEXT>
