<HEAD>Commissioner Rebuked Over Visit to Indian Reservation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Civil Rights Commission demanded Friday
that its chairman apologize for his actions on an Indian reservation
in Arizona last month, according to a published report.
   The chairman, William B. Allen, went to the White Mountain Apache
Reservation on Feb. 7 to look into a custody dispute involving a
14-year-old girl. Allen, a psychologist and a television crew
interviewed the girl, outraging tribal authorities who called the
incident an invasion of sovereignty.
   The New York Times reported in its Saturday editions that the
commission rebuked Allen during a closed meeting Friday, and ordered
him to write letters of apology to all involved.
   One member of the commission who attended the meeting said Allen
acknowledged he had exercised bad judgment, The Times reported.
   Allen has said he went to the reservation because he wanted
first-hand knowledge of whether the girl, Lalita Altaha, had had a
chance to express her own wishes in the custody dispute.
   The girl was adopted as an infant by a white couple, Nadine and
Normand Desrochers, but last year a court ordered that she be
returned to her natural mother, Thurza Altaha, who lives on the
White Mountain reservation.
   According to The Times' account, Allen learned of the case from
psychologist Barry Goodfield, who is a consultant to the commission
and who also had advised the Desrochers family. Allen told the
commission he went to the reservation with Goodfield, two U.S.
marshals and a camera crew which was making a documentary on Indian
adoption cases.
   Allen told the commissioners that they approached a school bus on
which Lalita was riding and asked for her, and that she agreed to
speak with them. They spoke with the girl for about 30 minutes, then
drove her in Goodfield's car to her home, where they had a ``tense''
exchange with Mrs. Altaha, Allen said.
   As Allen, Goodfield and the others were driving away from the
reservation, they were stopped by Gila County sheriff's deputies at
the request of tribal police and deteined for questioning. They were
released four or five hours later, said Sheriff Joe Rodriguez.
   Tribal chairman Reno Johnson later called the incident ``an
incursion that ... clearly violates the sovereignity'' of the tribe.
   At the commission's meeting Friday, Allen defended his actions as
an attempt to determine how tribal courts handle custody cases. The
commission then went into private session and demanded he write
letters of apology indicating that his activities were not approved
by the commission or condoned by its members, The Times reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

