<HEADLINE>  YOUNG INSPECTORS ON FRONT LINES OF A GRAVE
ENVIRONMENTAL BATTLE
MEXICO CITY KIDS PLUG WATER LEAKS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "I've seen a lot of leaks," he says, gravely.;    Since late May, Marco and
about 70,000 other preteens have worked as voluntary water inspectors, the
latest vanguard in Mexico City's urgent race to save water before supplies dry
up. In the crowd of environmental catastrophes that make up this monstrous
capital -- the world's most populous and most polluted urban area -- vanishing
water has caused even more alarm than poisonous air. The problem long ago made
California's notorious water crisis look like child's play.;    Against
appalling odds, however, are a few glimmers of hope. The children's crusade,
which officials say attracted the broadest voluntary involvement ever seen in
this city, is one of several dramatic environmental measures that have lately
marked the presidency of Carlos Salinas de Gortari.;    Environmental prize;  
 On June 7, Salinas won a United Earth award, an environmental prize sponsored
by the great-grandnephew of philanthropist Alfred Nobel. The news raised
eyebrows, coming in the midst of the worst pollution season ever seen here.
Yet it recognized recent efforts by Salinas, including his promotion of
low-lead gas and the Day Without a Car program, and his decision to shut down
the 18th of March oil refinery, long condemned as a major polluter in the
capital.;    The government is just beginning to take equally dramatic action
to stem its alarming depletion of water supplies.;    Mexico City's main water
problems are its 30,000 industries and enormous population. At 20 million
residents, that population is more than two-thirds the size of California's,
and growing by as much as 1 million a year.;    Factories and people have
steadily overused a main water source, the Lerma River, forcing the government
to bring in water from 78 miles outside the city. They are also using up
underground aquifers so fast that parts of the capital are actually sinking by
as much as 12 inches a year.;    Aztecs blamed;    "It's truly alarming," says
Salvador Gonzalez, who helped plan the children's inspection program. "We can
live without electricity, but not without water.";    A lot of the blame for
Mexico City's predicament lies with the Aztecs, who in the early 14th century
chose to build their civilization on a marshy island in this mountain-ringed
plateau more than 7,000 feet above sea level. Legend has it that the Aztec
leaders were guided to the site by their god, Huitzilopochtli, whose image was
a hummingbird.;    The deity allegedly told the Aztecs they would recognize
the promised land when they came upon a lake with a small island, where an
eagle perched on a cactus was devouring a snake. The leaders found their
eagle, cactus and snake in the Valley of Mexico, and the image now adorns the
Mexican flag.;    Spaniards drained lakes;    Yet the Aztecs couldn't have
imagined how much their new city of Tenochtitlan would grow, depleting its
precious resources. The Spaniards who took over in the 16th century drained
the valley's lakes and built canals. As the city grew, that water was steadily
used up by its people.;    Today, 10 percent of Mexico's national supply of
electricity is devoted just to bringing water to city residents from
surrounding lowlands, and up from wells within the city.;    Mexico City's
water consumption is roughly 70 gallons per person per day. That's similar to
levels in the United States, but officials here say it can't continue.;   
Unlike California, Mexico has not yet rationed water or fined residential
water wasters, though there are plans to start next year. So far, authorities
have simply urged more care.;    Seeking help in spreading the word, officials
this year turned to grade schools.;    60 percent wasted;    "Close to 60
percent of our water consumption is wasted," says Tomas Goyeneche, a spokesman
for a city water-efficiency program. "The adult already has bad training in
using resources, but children can still learn.";    Children, it seems, can
also teach. Armed with baseball caps and buttons identifying them as official
H2O Superinspectors, tens of thousands of them knocked on doors through most
of May and early June. They looked for leaks, offered advice and handed out
pamphlets on water conservation and rubber gaskets for on-the-spot repairs.
They also distributed surveys for homeowners to answer, with each completed
form an extra point in their favor in a capitalwide competition.;    "The kids
were received mostly very well," says Goyeneche, "whereas I can imagine, an
adult might have gotten mad at another adult telling him not to use a hose to
wash his car.";    Walkman, Nintendo prizes;    Walkman cassette players and
Nintendo games already have been awarded to winners in participating schools
and neighborhoods. And next week, Marco Hernandez, who has visited 489 homes,
will be given a personal computer for coming in first citywide.;    Marco and
the other superinspectors, all 9 to 10 years old, have urged their friends and
neighbors to take shorter showers, replace their toilets with smaller models
and turn off sink faucets while brushing their teeth.;    "We want these
children themselves to learn a whole new way of using water," says Rosalba
Salazar, a neighborhood coordinator for the water-efficiency program.;   
Marco is a shining example of the new Mexican she has in mind.;    The boy,
who wants to join the military when he grows up, says he'll keep inspecting
homes this summer, even though the contest has ended.;    Meanwhile, city
officials keep trying to come up with more ways to save water.;    Residents
have clamored for repairs in old pipes, whose leaks are blamed for 15 percent
of daily water use. Environmentalists are calling for strict rationing.;   
Yet most analysts agree that the only truly effective step would be to reduce
the Valley of Mexico's out-of-control population growth. And so far, there's
no sign of that happening.  </TEXT>
