<HEAD>Nebraska Blaze Contained; Endangered Trout Steered to Ash-free Waters</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with control of Boulder Canyon
blaze, quote from Boise center, details on other Colorado fire, other detail;
Picks up 7th graf, `Officials in ...'; SUBS 18th graf, `In Arizona ...'
to UPDATE with officials hoping to contain fire today.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters finished digging a fire lane around a blaze that
burned tens of thousands of acres in Nebraska, and officials in New
Mexico tried to steer endangered trout to waters free of ash from a
nearby forest fire.
   Crews were released from sites in several Western states
Wednesday as wet weather helped firefighters bring several blazes
under control.
   ``We have rain ... it's cooler and we've got firefighters going
home. Isn't that good news?'' asked U.S. Forest Service spokeswoman
Merle Young in Utah, where three fires burning on more than 20,000
acres were subdued.
   The number of firefighters battling active blazes was expected to
fall to around 5,000 today from more than 11,000 as recently as
Tuesday, the Boise Interagency Fire Center reported. Firefighters
were winding up work in Arizona, New Mexico, California, Colorado,
Wyoming, Utah and Nebraska.
   ``Every fire that we have has been contained or will be contained
today or Friday,'' Arnold Hartigan, spokesman at the Boise center,
said this morning. ``We're doing very well with the fires.''
   The weather forecast also continued to be good, with more rain
and higher humidity in most regions, he said.
   In Colorado, a half-inch of rain fell in Boulder Canyon, helping
crews fighting a 2,000-acre fire that destroyed 37 homes and damaged
19 other buildings. The blaze was contained, or surrounded,
Wednesday and declared under control this morning. A 2,600-acre fire
in Mesa Verde National Park was controlled without damaging ruins
left by 13th century Anasazi Indians.
   But a 2,000-acre blaze in Colorado's Poudre Canyon was still to
be contained, officials said, and they weren't planning on anything
more than a brief respite.
   ``If we had two days of 98 degrees, we'd be right back where we
were Sunday,'' said fire information officer Ed Nesselroad.
   Officials in California pushed back the target for containing a
2,900-acre fire in rough terrain near Big Sur to Friday evening,
said Maeton Freel, a Forest Service spokesman. More than 900
firefighters had contained a little more than half of the blaze,
which investigators believe was started by an arsonist, he said.
   A wildfire that temporarily shut busy Interstate 15 between the
San Gabriel and San Bernardino mountains east of Los Angeles was
partially contained before it could threaten a housing development,
authorities said. About 100 firefighters battled the blaze in
100-degree heat and 35 mph winds.
   Crews in northwest Nebraska used heavy equipment and shovels to
encircle a grass and tree fire in an area eight miles wide by 22
miles long.
   ``We have fully contained the fire,'' said Jerry Larson, deputy
state fire marshal. ``Full control could be a couple of days and an
exact estimate on burned acreage can be made after that.''
   After flying over the area, Larson scaled back the size of the
fire to between 50,000 and 100,000 acres from more than 100,000
acres. The Forest Service confirmed at least 48,000 acres had
burned, he said.
   The lightning-caused fire destroyed 14 unoccupied structures but
spared buildings in historic Fort Robinson, an old cavalry post
where Sioux Chief Crazy Horse was killed by his jailers.
   The blaze burned nearly half of 22,000-acre Fort Robinson State
Park, but officials planned to reopen it Friday, said state parks
chief Charles Duncan.
   ``I'm sure we'll get some people in here out of curiosity, but
this is still a beautiful place,'' he said.
   In southwest New Mexico, rainfall on Tuesday washed ash from a
10,000-acre blaze in the Gila National Forest into Diamond Creek,
threatening Gila trout, U.S. Forest Service spokeswoman Andrea
Garcia said.
   Biologists began luring the trout into a mile-long section of
clear water in the creek on Wednesday and planned to transfer the
fish to nearby holding areas today with helicopters and mules.
   Most fire crews headed home from the Gila fire, which was
contained Monday, as well as from two fires contained Wednesday in
El Malpais National Monument, which burned a total of about 5,400
acres, said Nancy Neskauskas of the state forestry office.
   In Arizona, firefighters hoped to contain today the last large
fires, a 800-acre fire near Lake Havasu City in the west-central
part of the state. Others began leaving for other states still
threatened by fires, and 360,000 acres in the Coconino and
Apache-Sitgreaves national forests in the northern and eastern
sections of the state were reopened to the public.
   ``We're winding down,'' said U.S. Bureau of Land Management
spokesman Gordon Warren.
   In eastern Utah, crews began going home after the 4,500-acre Ryan
Creek fire near the Colorado line was contained Wednesday evening.
Firefighters extinguished two other fires that burned nearly 18,000
acres, but officials still battled a 100-acre fire in steep terrain
in Desolation Canyon.
</TEXT>
