<HEAD>Biologists Rescue Rare Trout From Ashy Creek; Fires Contained Elsewhere</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `The creek ...,' to restore dropped word `began.'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SILVER CITY, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Biologists on Thursday used long-handled
nets to scoop an endangered species of trout from a creek polluted
with ash from a nearly beaten wild fire. Firefighters mopped up
blazes in five other Western states.
   The Gila trout, lured into a clear section of Diamond Creek a day
earlier, were collected along a three-quarter mile stretch and put
in holding tanks on the sides of mules or horses to be taken
eventually to an Apache fish hatchery.
   ``They are hoping to remove at least 300 of the fish from the
creek and more if possible,'' said Andrea Garcia, a U.S. Forest
Service spokeswoman.
   The creek was becoming choked by ash from a lightning-caused fire
in Gila National Forest that burned more than 10,000 acres before
being contained on Monday. The blaze began June 30 and burned 50
miles northeast of Silver City.
   The fire should be controlled in two to four days, Ms. Garcia
said.
   Fires in Arizona, California, Colorado, Nebraska and Utah were
largely contained Thursday. Firefighters mostly mopped up and
monitored hot spots.
   Ash kicked up by the New Mexico blaze had settled in Diamond
Creek, choking off oxygen and possibly boosting the water's
alkalinity.
   The netted fish were to be transported in 250-gallon aerated
tanks aboard two trucks to a hatchery run by the U.S. Bureau of
Indian Affairs on the Mescalero Apache Reservation in south-central
New Mexico, said Ms. Garcia.
   She said the fish are fairly hardy.
   Gila trout once were widespread in mountain streams in the Gila
River Basin. But timber cutting, overgrazing, irrigation and the
introduction of rainbow trout have diminished their numbers.
   The fish has been on the federal endangered species list since
1967.
   The rescue was undertaken by the state Department of Game and
Fish, the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service and the Forest Service.
   In Utah, fire bosses took a wait-and-see attitude Thursday on the
state's only active wildfire, a 100-acre blaze in an inaccessible
area of Desolation Canyon, 140 miles southeast of Salt Lake City.
The fire was within a mile of an Uintah and Ouray Indian reservation
and threatened important deer and elk winter ranges, said Bureau of
Land Management district manager Gene Nodine.
   ``If the fire does make a major run, we would have to wait until
it reached a more accessible, less hazardous area to actively
suppress it,'' he said.
   Humidity rose significantly in eastern Utah, helping firefighters
subdue a 4,500-acre fire 28 miles from Grand Junction, Colo. Thirty
miles to the northwest, firefighters demobilized after battling a
15,500-acre fire for more than a week.
   In California, a fire near the Ventana Wilderness in the Los
Padres National Forest was 70 percent contained. More than 1,500
firefighters were on the firelines at the blaze, which burned 3,087
acres. Three other fires were contained.
   Five of six fires that have blackened nearly 9,000 acres in
Colorado have been declared contained. The sixth, a 2,000-acre blaze
fire in north-central Colorado near Fort Collins, was 95 percent
contained, officials said.
   In Nebraska's northwest corner, the Fort Robinson fire, which
destroyed 10,000 acres of the 22,000-acre Fort Robinson State Park,
was contained with full control expected by Friday, said Fire Chief
Bill Gartner. The blaze destroyed 14 structures and injured nine
people, none seriously.
   Arizona firefighters battled a 225-acre fire next to the Mogollon
Rim in east-central Arizona and expected to contain it on Saturday.
Every other major fire in the state was declared contained
Wednesday. Some 3,000 acres burned.
</TEXT>
