<HEAD>Chicago Struggles to Cope With Measles Outbreak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,100 measles cases have been reported
in Chicago as it copes with the worst outbreak in the resurgence of
the disease this year.
   The national Centers for Disease Control said 1,123 measles cases
were reported to Chicago health officials through Aug. 23, and that
78 percent have occurred in preschool children. In the United
States, 9,650 measles cases have been reported in the United States,
compared with 2,151 in the 1988 period.
   The Chicago outbreak ``is similar to others among inner-city
populations in the United States in that it involves primarily
unvaccinated black and Hispanic preschool-aged children,'' the CDC
said. Blacks and Hispanics account for 94 percent of the Chicago
cases.
   Chicago authorities have set up at least seven new vaccination
clinics, which have administered at least 21,000 doses of measles
vaccine. Door-to-door teams have given at least 2,000 more doses,
and the CDC said vaccination clinics have also been set up in four
hospital emergency departments.
   Measles, a once-common childhood disease, was believed on the
verge of eradication in this country in the early '80s _ just 1,497
cases were reported in 1983 _ but case counts have increased since.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Federal Wildlife Officials to Split Whooping Crane Colony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAUREL, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal wildlife officials plan to split the
world's only captive colony of whooping cranes this November to
reduce the chance the flock could be wiped out by disease or natural
disaster.
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service said 22 of the 54 endangered
birds at the Patuxent Wildlife Research Center would be shipped to
the International Crane Foundation in Baraboo, Wis.
   ``The service has been concerned about having all of their eggs
in one basket, literally,'' said David Trauger, the center's deputy
director. ``The service felt it was the prudent thing to do, to
separate the breeding flocks, and there's enough breeders now to do
that.''
   The center started in 1987 to breed the rare birds under a joint
program with Canadian wildlife officials. The Wisconsin foundation
was selected as the home of the new flock after considering several
groups across the nation.
   Although the foundation has not bred whooping cranes, it has
successfully bred 13 of the 14 other existing species of cranes in
the world.
   Scientists hope that by successfully breeding whooping cranes in
captivity, they will be able to establish another flock in the wild.
An attempt to do that failed in 1975 when an experimental flock at
the Grays Lake National Wildlife Refuge in Idaho failed to produce
enough eggs to sustain the colony.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Apache Reservation Car Death Rate Seven Times Nation's</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Indian Health Service has determined that the
2,600-square-mile White Mountain Apache Reservation in eastern
Arizona has a car-crash death rate seven times that of the nation as
a whole.
   The national Centers for Disease Control said 24 people were
killed in crashes on the reservation in 1985-86, a rate of 129 per
100,000 people. That's nearly seven times higher than the U.S. rate
of 19 per 100,000 and three times the national rate for Indians and
Alaskan Natives of 43 per 100,000.
   Vehicle death rates go up as population density goes down, and
the rural location of the Arizona tribe, population 9,300, ``may
account in part for the elevated ... death rate,'' the CDC said.
   Pedestrians accounted for seven of the 24 fatalities, and the CDC
said new streetlights were installed along pedestrian routes in
December.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 11</NOTE>
