<LEADPARA>  LEAVE THE layered look at home, get ready to ski parts of the mountain you may
have been afraid to try before, and by all means, follow the sun.;    There's
nothing quite like going to the Sierra for a few days this time of year and
coming back with your mocha-colored face looking like you've been in a tanning
booth for a week.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Venture  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SPRING SKIING: CORN SNOW, T-SHIRTS AND A
GOOD TAN  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Venture -- Celebrating the Active Life  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     We're talking rites of spring here: skiing on silken carpets of corn snow;
checking out the action on the sun decks; gliding through the trees with the
greatest of ease.;    What follows is a suggested itinerary for the spring
skier at some of the most popular areas in the northern Sierra. Call ahead to
be sure your favorite area will be open.;     ALPINE MEADOWS: Alpine Meadows
flaunts its spring skiing by staying open until Memorial Day -- and with good
reason. The resort has terrain that faces nearly every point on the compass,
practically guaranteeing good snow somewhere on the mountain until late
afternoon.;     SQUAW VALLEY: Savvy skiers at Squaw Valley begin their spring
mornings on the intermediate slopes of Sun Bowl, accessible from the Cornice
II chair, and the advanced Sundance (formerly Tower 16) run.;    After 10
a.m., check out the East Face of KT-22 for advanced skiers, and Emigrant, Gold
Coast, East Broadway and Mainline for intermediates. Granite Chief has a
variety of exposures that begin softening after 10, and Shirley Lake and
Headwall reach prime conditions about noon, according Bob Cushman, assistant
ski patrol director.;     KIRKWOOD: The Elevator Shaft, a run not nearly so
fearsome as its name suggests, should be the first stop for corn snow buffs.
The intermediate slope, which can be reached from the Sunrise chair, has a
southern exposure and softens by about 10 a.m., said Kirkwood spokesman Mike
Allen.;     SUGAR BOWL: Mount Disney with its wide variety of exposures is the
best bet for spring skiing, according to Don Belden, Sugar Bowl's mountain
manager.;    By 10 a.m. the snow should be excellent on the East Face of
Disney, with its variety of glade and tree skiing. By noon, head for the runs
off the nose of Disney, and afternoon is the best time to hit the groomed runs
that veer down the western exposure of the mountain, Belden said.;    
HEAVENLY VALLEY: The Nevada side of Heavenly Valley is the best for morning
skiing, said Scotty Atchinson, a ski patrol supervisor. The lower part of the
Nevada side is closed for the season, so ride to the top of the California
side and ski the trails off the Dipper chair  </TEXT>
