<LEADPARA>  DEAR ANN -- Many parents lack consideration when they name their newborn
infants. I'd like to give your readers some guidelines. Their children will be
forever grateful.;   (check) Don't choose a name just because it is popular at
the moment. Ten years from now Jessica or Ashley will be one of eight in her
class with the same name.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  WHAT'S IN A NAME? A KID'S ENTIRE LIFE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Ann Landers is on vacation. This column is a reprint.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     (check) Don't name your child for a TV celebrity, movie star or sports
figure. In five years the star may be forgotten and you'll be sorry.;  
(check) Don't combine your husband's first name with a feminine ending and
invent something "cute" like Markella or Johnette. The kid will spend her
whole life spelling it for people.;   (check) Don't name the baby Herkimer or
some such name just because it has been in the family for a long time.;   --
Made My Mistakes and I'm Sorry;   DEAR SORRY -- Thanks for the advice. Too bad
you didn't let us know what you did to your children that prompted you to
write.; DEAR ANN -- The letter from the teen-ager whose father called him
belittling names brought back some heartbreaking memories.;   I was a tall
girl for my age. My dad took delight in calling me "The Big Ox" or "The Long
Drink of Water." I also had a crooked tooth in front. He never lost a chance
to call it to people's attention by asking, "How do you like our snaggle-tooth
witch?";   Because of my father's merciless belittling (Mom called it "teasing
a little"), I grew up self-conscious and shy. It wasn't until I left home for
college that I realized I was far from ugly and not much taller than most
girls my age. Although I still have moments of insecurity -- I'm in my 40s --
I've come to realize that my father did this to compensate for his own
feelings of inadequacy.;   -- Receiving End;   DEAR RECEIVING -- Your letter
contained almost all the advice I was prepared to give. Most parents who are
unable to show affection to their children were denied affection by their own
parents. Sometimes it takes therapy to break the chain.; DEAR ANN -- For
several years we have enjoyed entertaining our nieces and nephews before they
married. This way we were able to meet the new in-laws and families. Recently,
we were told, "Forget the fancy dinner party. Just add the cost to the price
of the gift.";   We were shocked and hurt. What should we do?;   -- P.W.L.;  
DEAR P.W.L -- Forget the fancy dinner party and give exactly what you would
have given prior to that tasteless suggestion.  </TEXT>
