<HL>
   Was Doc's Treasure
   A Fortune or Hoax?
   Gold Bugs Family
   ---
   Tale of Riches and Skeletons
   Sweeps From Jesse James
   To Missiles and Watergate
   ----
   By Robert Tomsho
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
03/22/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
</GV>
<LP>
   SANTA ANA, Calif. -- Everyone knew Doc Noss was a
character, but the story he told one day in 1937 was the
topper: While hunting on isolated Victorio Peak in New
Mexico, he had found 16 thousand gold bars. And not only
that: The gold was guarded by 27 skeletons lashed to wooden
posts.
   Two generations later, a model of Victorio Peak is
enshrined in a plastic cube in one corner of Terry Delonas's
cramped office here. "We want to open every cave in that peak
and solve this once and for all," says Mr. Delonas, the
42-year-old son of Doc's stepdaughter. "I don't want my
brother's children or my own offspring haunted by this for
another generation."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The story of the treasure of Victorio Peak is, in its own
way, a sweeping saga of America, wrapping together Jesse
James, nuclear weapons -- even Watergate. Now, finally, Doc's
mystery may be solved. With approval from the U.S. Congress
-- necessary because Victorio Peak is part of the top-secret
White Sands Missile Range -- the family can once again search
for the treasure. Digging could begin within months.
   The sombrero-shaped peak has plagued Mr. Delonas's family
for three generations and has been his obsession for a
decade. "There was a high level of frustration at watching my
grandmother being ignored and laughed at for decades," he
says. "When she died, I took up the gauntlet."
   In that time, he has abandoned a career in advertising,
borrowed money from relatives, driven a battered truck and
lived in rented rooms, all in the hope of mounting one last
search for the treasure. He has also persuaded friends and
acquaintances to pledge more than $1 million to hire lawyers,
lobbyists and engineers for the effort in return for a share
of the possible profits. He is general partner of the Ova
Noss Family Partnership, named for his long-suffering
grandmother.
   "I guess I'm not convinced there is something out there,
but I am convinced that they have the right to find out,"
says Santa Ana financial consultant Edward Carpenter, an
investor in the project. "They have the right to purge this
devil from their family."
   Still, like his grandmother before him, Mr. Delonas
remains a target for skeptics such as former New Mexico state
historian Myra Ellen Jenkins. After investigating the
Victorio Peak legend for two decades, she describes the story
as "absolutely ludicrous" and its source, Milton "Doc" Noss,
as "a con man."
   Doc, a traveling foot doctor who may or may not have had a
medical license, was known for his dead-eye marksmanship,
dark good looks and drunken binges. When he found the cache,
he said it consisted of Spanish artifacts, old Wells Fargo
chests and 100 tons of crude gold bars. "We can make John D.
Rockefeller look like a tramp," he is said to have told his
wife at the time.
   Doc supposedly hauled out between 80 and 200 gold bars,
burying most in the surrounding desert, but selling a few to
pay expenses. With private ownership of large amounts of gold
illegal at the time, local lawmen soon heard about this. An
Albuquerque-based agent of the U.S. Secret Service, in charge
of investigating gold cases for the Treasury Department,
looked into rumors that Doc was using the proceeds to buy
guns for Mexican revolutionaries. While that proved to be
false, Secret Service agents investigated Victorio Peak
rumors well into the 1960s.
   Meanwhile, an engineer Doc hired to widen the shaft
accidentally dynamited it shut in 1939. Doc subsequently
abandoned Ova and her children from her previous marriage.
Mrs. Noss and her children continued trying to reopen the
shaft after World War II. Doc Noss returned in 1949 with a
new bride and a Texas businessman who had agreed to bankroll
his efforts to reopen the cavern. Their partnership ended
badly a few months later: The Texan shot and killed Doc,
allegedly after Doc failed to deliver some gold bars as
promised. Self-defense, said the Texan.
   Chased from the site by the Army in 1955, Ova continued
battling the military for access. After some airmen from
nearby Hollowell Air Force Base claimed they had discovered a
cave full of gold at the peak, the Army and the Secret
Service secretly began digging in August 1961. For five days,
the airmen -- joined by military police, several military
officers and a Secret Service agent -- tried unsuccessfully
to find the cave again. One of the airmen later passed a lie
detector test.
   Work by the military continued intermittently until that
November, when two local cowboys wandered onto the effort.
They tipped off Ova Noss, who raised Cain with state
officials and got the dig stopped.
   In 1963, the Army allowed an expedition, including Mrs.
Noss, to search for the gold, but that expedition went broke
before its permit expired. Frustrated by frequent security
breaches by fortune hunters, the Army declared the case
closed.
   And it might have stayed that way if not for an apparently
offhand comment made by former White House counsel John Dean
during the 1973 Watergate hearings. Testifying about politics
in the Nixon White House, Mr. Dean said that attorney F. Lee
Bailey had asked former Attorney General John Mitchell
earlier that year for advice on how some unnamed clients
could legally remove a cache of gold bars hidden in the
Victorio Peak area.
   Although the Senate panel didn't delve further into the
issue, the mention on national television stirred up renewed
interest in the legend. That led the Army to allow a 1977 dig
by a contentious group of competing claimants that included
the Ova Noss family, Apache Indian leaders who believed
ancestors had hidden the treasure and a group claiming the
gold had been stashed away by their ancestor, Jesse James.
   That dig, too, proved fruitless. Such failures were a deep
disappointment for Mr. Delonas. Victorio Peak had been the
focal point of his childhood. His mother, aunts and uncles,
all stepchildren of Doc Noss, had all worked on the mystery.
Instead of reading comic books as a boy, Terry had listened
to his grandmother's treasure tales and sat in on her
meetings with lawyers and mining engineers. He had tagged
along when she stomped off to buttonhole local politicians or
barge in on missile range commanders.
   "You just could not be as close as I was to that woman and
not be driven to finish the game," says Mr. Delonas, who sold
his small New Mexico mail-order business after his
grandmother died in 1979 and devoted himself to carrying on
her legacy.
   Hoping to raise money, make political contacts and
possibly drum up Hollywood interest in the Victorio Peak
legend, he moved here to Southern California. To make ends
meet, he worked at various times as a supermarket controller,
a savings and loan advertising executive and a member of a
radioactive waste clean-up crew at a nuclear power plant. Mr.
Delonas is unmarried; his only brother has helped the cause
financially.
   During his free hours, Mr. Delonas relentlessly contacted
potential investors, senators and Pentagon officials. He
crisscrossed the country tracking down old documents and
videotaping interviews with aging associates of Ova and Doc.
More than a dozen people claimed to have seen parts of the
treasure trove.
   But other evidence, including a deposition from a state
mining engineer who said he had secretly had a bar tested
while Doc was drunk, seemed to indicate that at least some of
the "gold" bars Doc sold were actually brass or copper.
   Mr. Delonas is confident that better financing and
improved technology will allow the new dig to succeed where
others have failed. Unlike previous digs that relied on dusty
recollections, the current effort has involved the use of
sophisticated ground radar equipment to map potential
openings inside the mountain. Last year, that equipment
detected what appears to be an underground cavern in the
location Ova and Doc described.
   Mr. Delonas worries that another fortune hunter may have
located and removed the gold long ago. In rare moments, he
also fears that he could turn out to be the latest victim of
a spectacular con dreamed up decades ago. But he figures that
he and his family win no matter what. "We would love to make
a discovery," he says, "but even if we don't we've
accomplished our mission and laid to rest this mystery that
has plagued my family for three generations.
   "As a family, we rest in peace after this."
   ---
   Corrections &amp; Amplifications
                                                                                                       

   IN AN ARTICLE on the Victorio Peak gold legend, the airmen
who claimed to have discovered a cave full of gold at the
peak in 1961 were from Holloman Air Force Base in New Mexico.
The facility's name was incorrectly stated in Friday's
edition.
   (WSJ March 25, 1991)
